 This avoids redundant parsing/validation when config unchanged\n\n**Atomic Config Swap:**\nPrometheus distributes config changes to multiple subsystems via `ApplyConfig()` methods:\n\n1. `cmd/prometheus/main.go` - The `reloadConfig()` function:\n   - Loads config via `config.LoadFile()`\n   - Iterates through reloader functions (scrape manager, remote storage, alerting, rules, etc.)\n   - Each reloader's `ApplyConfig(conf)` method handles its portion of configuration\n   - If any reloader fails, entire reload fails and old config remains active\n   - Sets success metrics regardless, allowing monitoring of reload status\n\n2. `scrape/manager.go` - ApplyConfig pattern:\n   - Uses `reflect.DeepEqual(sp.config, cfg)` to detect scrape config changes per job\n   - Uses buffered channel `canReload` to limit concurrent pool reloads\n   - Spawns goroutine per pool to call `sp.reload(cfg)`\n   - Deletes removed pools, updates changed pools in parallel\n   - Returns error if any pool reload fails\n\n3. `scrape/scrape.go` - The `reload()` method:\n   - Updates pool's config reference\n   - Creates new HTTP client from updated config\n   - Calls `restartLoops()` with reuse flag\n   - In `restartLoops()`: for each existing scrape loop, either reuses scrape cache or creates new one\n   - Spawns new scrape loop with updated config but preserves target state and active connections\n   - Closes old HTTP client after new loops started\n   - This ensures no dropped metrics during scrape config changes\n\n4. `tsdb/db.go` - ApplyConfig applies storage config changes:\n   - Updates retention duration atomically via `atomic.Store()`\n   - Updates exemplar and out-of-order time window settings\n   - Calls `head.ApplyConfig()` for in-memory metrics changes\n\n5. `notifier/manager.go` - ApplyConfig for alertmanager discovery:\n   - Applies new alerting configuration\n   - Uses hash matching to preserve existing send loops when possible\n   - Only stops/creates alertmanager connections for changed configs\n\nKey Prometheus pattern: Config hash drives reload decisions → Single `reloadConfig()` function parses once → Multiple `ApplyConfig()` methods atomically update each subsystem → No process restart, existing scrape loops and queries continue uninterrupted.\n\n### Common Patterns\n\nBoth Kubernetes and Prometheus implement:\n1. **File Watchers**: fsnotify for event-driven reloads\n2. **Diff Detection**: Content hashing (SHA256/bytes.Equal) for fast change detection  \n3. **Two-Stage Validation**: Quick hash check, then detailed validation to prevent TOCTOU race conditions\n4. **Work Queues**: Backoff/retry semantics for failed reloads\n5. **Atomic Swaps**: Go's atomic.Value or single-threaded guarantees to swap config without locks\n6. **No Process Restart**: New connections/requests get new config, existing ones continue with old config until completion\n7. **Error Handling**: Failed reloads keep old config active, record metrics, and retry asynchronously"
